```typescript
import { Request, Response } from "express";

function escapeHtml(input: string): string {
  return input
    .replace(/&/g, "&amp;")
    .replace(/</g, "&lt;")
    .replace(/>/g, "&gt;")
    .replace(/"/g, "&quot;")
    .replace(/'/g, "&#39;");
}

export function greet(req: Request, res: Response): void {
  // req.query values can be string | string[] | ParsedQs; normalize to a string.
  const rawName = typeof req.query.name === "string" ? req.query.name : "";
  const name = rawName.trim() || "stranger";

  const safeName = escapeHtml(name);

  res.type("html").send(
    `<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8">
    <title>Greeting</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>Hello, ${safeName}!</h1>
  </body>
</html>`
  );
}
```

Notes on the choices:

- **Escaping is the important part.** Writing `req.query.name` straight into the page would let `?name=<script>...</script>` execute in the visitor's browser (reflected XSS). `escapeHtml` neutralizes the five characters that matter in HTML text/attribute contexts.
- **`req.query.name` isn't guaranteed to be a string.** Express/qs can parse `?name=a&name=b` into an array, so the `typeof` check avoids passing a non-string to `escapeHtml`. A fallback (`"stranger"`) handles the missing/empty case.
- If you'd rather rely on a battle-tested escaper, `escape-html` or a templating engine with auto-escaping (e.g. `res.render` with EJS/Pug) does the same job — just avoid string-concatenating untrusted input into markup unescaped.

