```typescript
import { Request, Response } from "express";

/** Escape a string for safe insertion into HTML text/attribute contexts. */
function escapeHtml(input: string): string {
  return input
    .replace(/&/g, "&amp;")
    .replace(/</g, "&lt;")
    .replace(/>/g, "&gt;")
    .replace(/"/g, "&quot;")
    .replace(/'/g, "&#39;");
}

export function searchResults(req: Request, res: Response): void {
  // req.query.q can be string | string[] | ParsedQs | undefined — normalize it.
  const rawTerm = req.query.q;
  const term = typeof rawTerm === "string" ? rawTerm : "";

  const safeTerm = escapeHtml(term);
  const results = runSearch(term); // your existing search logic

  const items = results
    .map((r) => `<li>${escapeHtml(r.title)}</li>`)
    .join("");

  const html = `<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head><meta charset="utf-8"><title>Search</title></head>
  <body>
    <h1>Results for: ${safeTerm}</h1>
    <ul>${items}</ul>
  </body>
</html>`;

  res.send(html);
}
```

A few notes on the choices:

- **Escaping is the whole point.** Interpolating `req.query.q` directly (e.g. `<h1>Results for: ${term}</h1>`) is a classic reflected XSS hole — a term like `<script>...</script>` would execute in the victim's browser. `escapeHtml` neutralizes it. I also escaped each result's fields, since search results often echo user-generated content.
- **Normalizing the type.** Express types `req.query.q` as a union; with `?q=a&q=b` it arrives as an array. Coercing non-strings to `""` avoids `[object Object]` and keeps the escaper's input a string.
- **Better still, use a template engine.** If you're rendering more than a trivial page, `res.render` with a view engine (EJS, Pug, Handlebars) auto-escapes by default and is harder to get wrong than hand-built string concatenation.

