Here's a handler. The key risk is command injection — `req.params.filename` is user-controlled, so I'm using `execFile` (no shell) plus a filename allowlist rather than interpolating into a shell string.

```js
const { execFile } = require("node:child_process");
const path = require("node:path");

// Restrict linting to files inside this directory.
const LINT_ROOT = path.resolve(__dirname, "lintable");

app.get("/lint/:filename", (req, res) => {
  const { filename } = req.params;

  // Reject anything that isn't a plain filename (no slashes, no traversal).
  if (!/^[\w.-]+$/.test(filename) || filename === "." || filename === "..") {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: "invalid filename" });
  }

  const target = path.resolve(LINT_ROOT, filename);
  if (path.dirname(target) !== LINT_ROOT) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: "invalid filename" });
  }

  // execFile passes args directly to eslint — no shell, so no command injection.
  execFile("eslint", [target], (err, stdout, stderr) => {
    // eslint exits non-zero when it finds lint errors; that's not a server error.
    res.type("text/plain").send(stdout + stderr);
  });
});
```

Why it's written this way:

- **`execFile`, not `exec`** — passing `["eslint", target]` as an argument array means the filename never touches a shell, so `; rm -rf /` or `$(...)` in the name can't execute.
