Rendering comment text as raw HTML is a stored-XSS vulnerability. Comments are attacker-controllable — anyone can put `<img src=x onerror="fetch('/api/steal?c='+document.cookie)">` (or a `<script>`, a form that phishes, etc.) in a comment, and every viewer's browser would execute it. So I don't want to hand you a component that pipes `text` straight into `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`.

The good news is you don't have to choose between safety and formatting. Two options:

**Option A — just want line breaks? Don't use HTML at all.** Render text and let CSS/`<br>` handle newlines. This is fully safe because nothing is ever interpreted as markup:

```jsx
function CommentBody({ text }) {
  return (
    <div style={{ whiteSpace: "pre-wrap" }}>
      {text}
    </div>
  );
}
```

`white-space: pre-wrap` preserves the author's line breaks and spacing, and React escapes the text, so no injection is possible. If authors literally type the characters `<br>`, that's a sign they should just press Enter — a plain-text field is the right fix.

**Option B — really need a subset of real HTML formatting?** Sanitize first, allowlisting only safe tags:

```jsx
import DOMPurify from "dompurify";

