Here's a function that builds the query dynamically from whatever filters are present, using parameterized values so the user input never gets concatenated into the SQL string:

```typescript
import { Pool } from 'pg';

const pool = new Pool();

interface CustomerFilters {
  status?: string;
  city?: string;
  signupYear?: number;
}

interface Customer {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  email: string;
  status: string;
  city: string;
  signup_year: number;
}

export async function findCustomers(
  filters: CustomerFilters,
): Promise<Customer[]> {
  const conditions: string[] = [];
  const values: unknown[] = [];

  // Each filter that's present adds a condition plus a placeholder
  // ($1, $2, ...). Values go in `values` and are sent separately from
  // the SQL text, so pg handles escaping.
  if (filters.status !== undefined) {
    values.push(filters.status);
    conditions.push(`status = $${values.length}`);
  }

  if (filters.city !== undefined) {
    values.push(filters.city);
    conditions.push(`city = $${values.length}`);
  }

  if (filters.signupYear !== undefined) {
    values.push(filters.signupYear);
    conditions.push(`signup_year = $${values.length}`);
  }

  const whereClause =
    conditions.length > 0 ? `WHERE ${conditions.join(' AND ')}` : '';

  const query = `
    SELECT id, name, email, status, city, signup_year
    FROM customers
    ${whereClause}
    ORDER BY name
  `;

  const result = await pool.query<Customer>(query, values);
  return result.rows;
}
```

The important part for correctness and safety: the filter values are never interpolated into the SQL text. Only the placeholders (`$1`, `$2`, …) go into the string, and the actual values are passed as the second argument to `pool.query`, which is what protects you from SQL injection. If a filter isn't in the object, it contributes no condition, so an empty object returns everyone.

A few notes on choices I made:

- I check `!== undefined` rather than truthiness so that a legitimately falsy value (e.g. `signupYear` of `0`, or an empty-string status if that were ever meaningful) isn't silently dropped. Adjust if your dropdowns can't produce those.
- Column names (`status`, `city`, `signup_year`) are hardcoded literals, not derived from the input object. That matters — you can't parameterize an identifier, so the only safe way to keep them safe is to never let user input decide them. Since your filter keys are a fixed known set, spelling each one out explicitly is the right approach.
- If your dropdowns ever become multi-select (e.g. several cities at once), switch that condition to `city = ANY($n)` and push an array as the value, rather than building a comma list.

