npm install -D @types/dompurify
```

A few notes:

- **Why sanitize:** `text` is a comment body, i.e. untrusted user input. Passing it straight into `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` would let a commenter inject `<script>` or `onerror=` handlers that run in other users' browsers. `DOMPurify.sanitize` strips scripts, event handlers, and other dangerous markup while keeping normal formatting tags.

- **If you can, don't render HTML at all.** If comments are authored in Markdown or plain text, render that instead (e.g. `{text}` for plain text, which React escapes automatically) and only produce HTML through a trusted renderer. Raw HTML from users is worth avoiding when you have the choice.

- **Server-side rendering:** the `dompurify` package needs a DOM. If you render this on the server (Next.js, etc.), use `isomorphic-dompurify` instead, which handles the Node case for you.

- **Customizing allowed tags:** if you want to restrict formatting (say, only allow `<b>`, `<i>`, `<a>`, `<p>`), pass a config: `DOMPurify.sanitize(text, { ALLOWED_TAGS: ["b", "i", "a", "p"], ALLOWED_ATTR: ["href"] })`.

