Rendering user-submitted text as raw HTML is a classic stored-XSS hole: one commenter writes `<img src=x onerror=...>` or `<script>` and it runs in every other reader's browser, stealing sessions and so on. So the component needs to render HTML *but* sanitize it first, allowing only the safe formatting tags you actually want.

Here's the component using [DOMPurify](https://github.com/cure53/DOMPurify), the standard for this:

```jsx
import DOMPurify from 'dompurify';

// Only the simple formatting tags authors are allowed to use.
const ALLOWED_TAGS = ['b', 'i', 'em', 'strong', 'br', 'p', 'a', 'ul', 'ol', 'li', 'blockquote'];
const ALLOWED_ATTR = ['href', 'title'];

export function CommentBody({ text }) {
  const clean = DOMPurify.sanitize(text ?? '', {
    ALLOWED_TAGS,
    ALLOWED_ATTR,
    // Block javascript:/data: URLs in any surviving href
    ALLOWED_URI_REGEXP: /^(?:https?|mailto):/i,
  });

  return (
    <div
      className="comment-body"
      dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: clean }}
    />
  );
}
```

Install the dependency:

```bash
npm install dompurify
```

A few things worth knowing:

- **Sanitize, don't escape.** If you just escaped everything, the author's `<b>` would show up as literal text. DOMPurify keeps the tags on your allow-list and strips everything else (`<script>`, event handlers like `onerror`, `javascript:` URLs), so formatting survives but attacks don't.
- **Tune the allow-list to what you actually support.** I included links, lists, and blockquotes; trim them if your editor only offers bold/italic/line-break. Smaller allow-list, smaller attack surface.
- **Links from strangers:** the `ALLOWED_URI_REGEXP` blocks `javascript:` and `data:` hrefs. You'll likely also want `rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer"` and `target="_blank"` added to rendered anchors — DOMPurify can do this via an `afterSanitizeAttributes` hook if you want, since comment links are untrusted.
- **Server-side rendering:** DOMPurify needs a DOM. In the browser it works as-is; if you render this on the server (Next.js, etc.), run it through `jsdom` (`DOMPurify(new JSDOM('').window)`) or, better, sanitize once when the comment is saved and store the clean version.

The one thing to avoid is dropping `text` straight into `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` without the sanitize step — that's the version that ships the vulnerability. Want me to add the `nofollow`/`target` link hook or a server-side sanitize helper for where comments are stored?

