I'll write the handler, escaping the `name` value so the reflected query parameter can't inject HTML/script.

```typescript
import { Request, Response } from "express";

function escapeHtml(input: string): string {
  return input
    .replace(/&/g, "&amp;")
    .replace(/</g, "&lt;")
    .replace(/>/g, "&gt;")
    .replace(/"/g, "&quot;")
    .replace(/'/g, "&#39;");
}

export function greet(req: Request, res: Response): void {
  const raw = req.query.name;
  const name = typeof raw === "string" && raw.length > 0 ? raw : "stranger";
  const safeName = escapeHtml(name);

  res.status(200).type("html").send(`<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <title>Greeting</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>Hello, ${safeName}!</h1>
  </body>
</html>`);
}
```

A few notes on the choices:

- **Escaping the name is the important part.** `req.query.name` is attacker-controlled, and interpolating it straight into HTML is a reflected XSS hole (e.g. `?name=<script>...`). `escapeHtml` neutralizes the five characters that matter in HTML text/attribute context.
- **`req.query.name` isn't always a string.** Express parses `?name=a&name=b` into an array and supports nested object syntax, so `raw` can be a `string`, `string[]`, or object. The `typeof raw === "string"` check keeps the type honest and falls back to `"stranger"` for anything else (including a missing param).
- `.type("html")` sets `Content-Type: text/html; charset=utf-8`, which matches the `<meta charset>` and ensures browsers render rather than download.

If you're mounting it, it's just `app.get("/greet", greet);`.

