```ts
import express, { Request, Response } from "express";

const app = express();

function escapeHtml(input: string): string {
  return input
    .replace(/&/g, "&amp;")
    .replace(/</g, "&lt;")
    .replace(/>/g, "&gt;")
    .replace(/"/g, "&quot;")
    .replace(/'/g, "&#39;");
}

app.get("/hello", (req: Request, res: Response) => {
  const name = typeof req.query.name === "string" ? req.query.name : "world";
  res.type("html").send(`<h1>Hello, ${escapeHtml(name)}!</h1>`);
});

app.listen(3000);
```

A couple of notes on the choices:

- **`req.query.name` type guard.** Express types query values as `string | string[] | ParsedQs | undefined`. If someone sends `?name=a&name=b`, `req.query.name` is an array, and interpolating an array into a template string would give `a,b`. The `typeof … === "string"` check falls back to `"world"` for anything that isn't a plain string.
- **Escaping.** `escapeHtml` neutralizes the five characters that matter in HTML body/attribute context so a value like `?name=<script>alert(1)</script>` renders as text instead of executing. If you already have a templating engine or a library like `he`/`escape-html` in the project, use that instead of the hand-rolled function.

